1 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Preemption. This chapter abrogates the common law of public nuisance
2 and private nuisance in this state and supersedes any other state statute to the extent there is a conflict TO THE
3 EXTENT COMMON LAW IS INCONSISTENT WITH THIS CHAPTER.
4
5 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Liability for a public nuisance. (1) A person may be liable under
6 SUBJECT TO a public nuisance cause of action only if that person proximately caused the public nuisance at the
7 time the public nuisance was created, which includes controlling, OR INSTRUCTING ANOTHER PERSON TO ENGAGE
8 IN, the unlawful activity that proximately caused the public nuisance. Public nuisance is not a strict liability
9 offense.
10 (2) Every successive owner of property who neglects to abate a continuing public nuisance upon
11 or in the use of the property that was created by a former owner is liable for the public nuisance in the same
12 manner as the one who first created it.
13 (3) No lapse of time can legalize a public nuisance amounting to an actual obstruction of public
14 right.
15
16 NEW SECTION. Section 5. Public nuisance actions by government. (1) A public nuisance cause
17 of action is available to a government entity only if the public nuisance is within the jurisdiction of that
18 government entity. Past, current, or future expenditures made by a government entity related to injunction of or
19 any other response to a public nuisance does not itself confer standing to file or maintain a public nuisance
20 action.
21 (2) In a public nuisance action brought by a government entity, the only remedies against a public
22 nuisance are:
23 (a) indictment or information as regulated by Titles 45 and 46;
24 (b) injunctive relief to enjoin an unlawful activity that is proximately causing a public nuisance; and
25 (c) monetary and nonmonetary resources, if quantifiable, that a court determines are reasonably
26 necessary to abate the public nuisance based on relevant and reliable cost factors and established by clear and
27 convincing evidence. All resources provided under this subsection (2) must be spent to abate the public
