13 NEW SECTION. Section 6. Private cause of action for public nuisance. (1) A public nuisance
14 cause of action is available to a private person only if that person has sustained a special injury proximately
15 caused by the public nuisance and only if the person can show the existence of the special injury by clear and
16 convincing evidence.
17 (2) A special injury is an injury that is different in kind, not just in degree, from an injury sustained
18 by the general public exercising the same public right. A SPECIAL INJURY IS NOT ONE BASED UPON IMPAIRMENT OF
19 THE SPIRITUAL, CULTURAL, OR EMOTIONAL SIGNIFICANCE ASSOCIATED WITH A NAVIGABLE LAKE, RIVER, BAY, STREAM,
20 CANAL, OR BASIN OR A PUBLIC PARK, SQUARE, STREET, ROAD, OR HIGHWAY.
21 (3) Financial expenditures made by a private person related to an injunction of, or any other
22 response to, a public nuisance does not constitute a special injury sufficient to confer standing on the person to
23 file or maintain a public nuisance action.
24 (4) The remedy available to a private person in a public nuisance action is limited solely to
25 compensatory damages for the special injury.
26 (5) The abatement of a public nuisance pursuant to 27-30-204 does not preclude the right of a
27 person to recover compensatory damages under this section.
